<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Keoghs response to the TSC call for evidence, December 2013</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Written evidence from </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Keoghs </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(CMI0007)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#006699; font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">About Keoghs</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">Keoghs is the only “top </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">100</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">” law firm to focus exclusively on the handling and defence of both mainstream and specialist insurance claims.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> We offer an “end to end” claims service</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> to insurers, public sector bodies and self-insured corporate</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> which includes pre-litigation, litigation and costs negotiation activities.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> We represent insurers who, between them, provide around 70% of the motor insurance purchased in the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> With almost</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> 1,200 dedicated staff Keoghs is a recognised leader in the field.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> In the last 12 months we have been instructed to handle in excess of 35,000 separate matters in total across all classes of personal injury claim.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">Keoghs has been closely engaged in the b</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">roader Government reforms to the civil litigation system as enacted in Part 2 of the LASPO Act 2012 and other ancillary CPR changes as recommended by Lord Justice Jackson.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#006699; font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#006699; font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">We welcomed the Committee’s Fourth Report on “Cost of Motor Insura</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">nce: Whiplash” released on </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">31</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:6.67pt; vertical-align:super">st</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> July 2013</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">. Whilst there were some points upon which we disagreed, we saw the overall response as both balanced and pragmatic. We have also seen Mrs </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">Ellman’s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> letter of 29</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:6.67pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> October to the Secretary of State for Justice. We concur that whilst the Government’s own response to the whiplash issue should be broadly welcomed, that response was light on detail and timeframes. Certain key points raised were simply not mentioned and </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">as always, our concern is that “the devil will be in the detail”.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">We will deal with what we consider to be the key outstanding points in turn:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#3366ff; font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Whiplash medical evidence</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">We have concerns regarding the scope of any reform. Since the implementation of the</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> April and July reforms, we have seen quite marked changes in tactics and approach by certain claimant law firms. In order to recover lost revenue as a result of the reduction in the fixed fee, additional medical reports being obtained for simple, modest w</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">hiplash claims is rapidly becoming commonplace. These reports are predominantly produced by psychologists and / or rehabilitation providers. The reports add little to the claim in terms of insight - the rehabilitation is often no more than a </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">DVD</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> posted to </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">the claimant or some telephone based advice. The psychologist input talks of travel anxiety, flashbacks </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">etc</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> which settles in a matter of days or weeks. These additional reports combined can add up to £1600 in </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">additional </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">costs and are often obtained </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">from</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> th</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">e law firms own medical agency. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">We would add that sometimes these very early medical interventions appear contrary to NICE guidelines and to the detriment of the claimant. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">This is simply a manipulation of the process to recover revenue. The Government must</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> move via CPR or process change to head this off before it becomes the norm. This obviously negates the overall ambition to reduce premium.</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">Given the above, we would like to understand how the Government will deliver truly independent and accredited medic</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">al evidence. The Legal Services Act allows </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">ABS</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> structures whilst LASPO bans referral fees. The Government now wishes to dismantle relationships between law firms and</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> their </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">owned medical agencies. We see competing legislation / strategy here and would like </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">more detail on how Government plan to square this particular </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">circle.</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">medical expert must be given detail of the mechanics of the accident. This has to be a fundamental part of the process. This could be incorporated into a standard template report whe</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">re the expert provides opinion as to the stated injury against the accident circumstances. Experts have previously confirmed whiplash symptoms unaware that a simple clash of wing mirrors had taken place.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> We would also suggest that the defendant be returned</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> the right to request a review of medical notes in cases. We believe that this could again serve as a deterrent against fraud or speculative claims.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">We see accreditation and then policing as key. We do not want to go through a process where we simply </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">validate and re-badge what already exists. Any new process must be monitored to ensure that it is delivering improved outcomes.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> We are concerned that Government are unsighted on just how little governance and best practice currently exists in the sphere of</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> medico-legal reporting. Real and meaningful reform is required not simply flexing what already exists.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">We do not agree that a stipulation should exist that a claimant should see a medical expert within “X” days of the accident occurring. This would place</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> an unacceptable burden on an already overstretched NHS front line.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> Such a stipulation may also breach clinical best practice and in some instances, NICE guidelines on pathways to care.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> Assuming we have genuinely independent and accredited experts who are </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">aware of the accident circumstances, this should drive change.</span><br /><br /><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ul><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.49pt; padding-left:4.51pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#3366ff; font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Third Party Fraud</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></li><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">We welcome the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">TSC</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">’s insistence that the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">MoJ</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> fully articulate their position on this very important point. Historically, the insurance industry has been criticised for not</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> doing enough to combat fraud (unfairly in our view) but now we find the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">MoJ</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> reticent to deliver key change to support the fight against insurance fraud.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">The Law Commission have recently sought views on whether they should re-visit this key issue. Sixteen</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> out of eighteen respondents confirmed that they should. It was notable that only APIL and Thompson’s Solicitors favoured the status quo. The now </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">well known</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> case of Summers &amp; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">Fairclough</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> Homes is clear evidence that re</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">form is compelling. The fact that</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> a cla</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">imant who amplified his claim tenfold was not deemed to be “exceptional” and was still awarded damages speaks volumes for the current position. Again, this reluctance to tackle serious fraud negates the wish to see lower premiums for hard</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> pressed consumers</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">. W</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">e suspect those very consumers would be very much in favour of reform in this area, where they to be aware of the current situation.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">Finally on this point, we would wish to raise again the issue of cash inducements. The </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">CMC</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> Regulator has now banned any form of inducement to bring a claim. The </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">SRA</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> have declined to mirror that position for claimant lawyers. We still regularly see offers of up to £2000 cash, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">ipads</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> and being placed in a draw to win holidays </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">etc</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> by claimant lawye</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">rs. These inducements drive up frequency and encourage speculative claims. They should be banned. We do not agree that this will impede access to justice - gen</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">uinely injured victims will always</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> seek redress and do not need to </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">be </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">financially coaxed to do so</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">.</span><br /><br /><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ul><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.49pt; padding-left:4.51pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#3366ff; font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">RTA Limitation periods</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">.</span><br /><br /><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></li><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">We again welcome the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">TSC</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">’s pressure on this issue. We do not agree with the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">MoJ</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> response that essentially, it would be too difficult to make this change. The Act could simply be amended to alter RTA personal injury limitation </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">to say, 12 months. This would then stop “farming” of aged books of potential claims - from our experience a frequent source of fraudulent claims.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">We are aware of one claimant law firm who are regularly presenting “new” claims where the period back to the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">actual accident date is often in excess of 600 days. This is clear evidence of farming and of individuals being coaxed into presenting claims. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">Given the current state of knowledge surrounding RTA compensation we do not believe that limitation should be any</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> more than 12 months. The Act retains Judicial discretion and so safeguards exist for the protection of innocent victims who may not be aware of their rights immediately.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ul></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.49pt; padding-left:4.51pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#3366ff; font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Small Claims Track</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">.</span><br /><br /><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></li><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">Whilst we welcome</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">d the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">TSC</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">’s narrative that there were strong</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> arguments for increasing the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">SCT</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">, we were disappointed that you could not then support change. We would be interested to learn from the Committee what safeguards would need to be in place to allow you to support an increase to £5000?</span><br /><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">LASPO introduced Dam</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">ages Based Agreements for personal injury claims. If the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">SCT</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> were increased to £5000 then this is how many claimants would fund their claims. This is in practice</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> no different</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> to what is happening now, with most claimants ceding 25% of their damages to the</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">ir lawyer under a CFA. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">To protect claimants further then should the SCT be increased in the future, we would strongly advocate for a predictable damages tool (supported by Jackson LJ) to offer further consumer protection and transparency.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> </span><br /><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ul></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.49pt; padding-left:4.51pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#3366ff; font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Data Sharing</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">.</span><br /><br /><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></li><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">We would certainly support a level of data sharing as between compensators and claimant representatives. We envisage that this would operate at a fairly high level and enable claimant lawyers to make rapid checks against their potential clients claims hi</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">story. This would certainly help the fraud filtering system and act as a further deterrent against fraudulent claims.</span><br /><br /><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ul></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="color:#3366ff; font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="color:#3366ff; font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusions</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">We welcome the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">TSC</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">’s continued engagement and scrutiny in this important policy area.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">We have articulated our concerns and would welcome the chance to discuss these further with members of the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">TSC</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">. We would also express an over-arching concern in terms of timeframes. We are all of course aware that an Election will take place in May 2015. R</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">ealistically therefore, much of this important work will have to be undertaken and delivered against in the next 12 months. The </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">MoJ</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> have stated tha</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">t they intend to work “at pace”</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> - a comment which we welcome.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">It is now for all stakeholders to support the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">MoJ</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt"> in their work and to help both the Committee and Government to implement meaningful change which will ultimately benefit the end consumer in the form of reduced motor premiums.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><br /><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>